    "# Importation de modules n√©cessaires\n",

    "t = np.arange(0, 10, 0.1)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Fr√©quence de la sinuso√Øde\n",

    "\n",
    "# Sinuso√Øde : c'est tout simple, il suffit d'√©crire l'expression math√©matique üòé\n",
    "w = np.sin(2*math.pi*f*t)\n",
    "\n",

    "plt.plot(t,w)\n",

    "t = np.arange(0, 10, 0.01)\n",
    "params = [[2, .5, 2], [2, 2, 2], [2, .5, 1]]\n",
    "\n",
    "for p in params:\n",
    "    A, a, f = p\n",

    "    y = A * np.multiply(y1, y2)\n",
    "\n",

    "## Produit de convolution\n",
    "\n",
    "Pour chacun des couples de signaux suivants, repr√©sentez $x$, $y$ et le produit de convolution $x*y$.\n",
    "Attention √† sp√©cifier l'argument `mode=\"same\"` dans la fonction `numpy.convolve`.\n",
    "\n",
    "* Repr√©sentez sur l'intervalle $n \\in \\{-10,\\dots,10\\}$ les signaux $x$ et $y$, et le produit de convolution $x*y$ :\n",
    "\n",
    "  $$\n",
    "    x[n] = \\sin(2\\pi n/10)\n",
    "    \\quad\\text{et}\\quad\n",
    "    y[n] =\n",
    "    \\begin{cases}\n",
    "      3 \\quad\\text{si}\\quad n=5 \\\\\n",
    "      0 \\quad\\text{sinon}\n",
    "    \\end{cases}\n",
    "   $$\n",
    "\n",
    "* Repr√©sentez sur l'intervalle $n \\in \\{-10,\\dots,10\\}$ les signaux $x$ et $y$, et le produit de convolution $x*y$ :\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "    x[n] =\n",
    "    \\begin{cases}\n",
    "      1 \\quad\\text{si}\\quad n\\in\\{-1,1\\} \\\\\n",
    "      2 \\quad\\text{si}\\quad n=0 \\\\\n",
    "      0 \\quad\\text{sinon}\n",
    "    \\end{cases}\n",
    "    \\quad\\text{et}\\quad\n",
    "    y[n] =\n",
    "    \\begin{cases}\n",
    "      -1 \\quad\\text{si}\\quad n=-1 \\\\\n",
    "      1 \\quad\\text{si}\\quad n=1 \\\\\n",
    "      0 \\quad\\text{sinon}\n",
    "    \\end{cases}\n",
    " $$\n",
    "\n",
    "* Repr√©sentez sur l'intervalle $n \\in \\{-200,\\dots,200\\}$ le signal enregistr√© dans le fichier [signal2.csv](http://vincmazet.github.io/signal1/_static/tp/signal2.csv) et $y$ d√©fini√© ci-dessous, ainsi que leur produit de convolution.\n",
    "\n",
    "  $$\n",
    "    y[n] =\n",
    "    \\begin{cases}\n",
    "      1/10 \\quad\\text{si}\\quad n\\in\\{0,\\dots,9\\} \\\\\n",
    "      0 \\quad\\text{sinon}\n",
    "    \\end{cases}\n",
    "  $$"

    "def plotconv(x, y, ylim, line=\".\"):\n",
    "    \n",
    "    titles = [\"x\", \"y\", \"x*y\"]\n",
    "    z = np.convolve(x, y, mode=\"same\")\n",
    "\n",
    "    plt.figure(figsize=(15,4))\n",
    "    i = 0\n",
    "    for s in [x, y, z]:\n",
    "        plt.subplot(1,3,i+1)\n",
    "        plt.plot(n,s,line)\n",
    "        plt.title(f\"${titles[i]}$\")\n",
    "        plt.ylim(ylim)\n",
    "        i += 1\n",
    "    plt.show()"
   ]

    "\\end{questions}\n",
    "\n",
    "La suite de l'exercice a pour objectif d'illustrer l'int√©r√™t de repr√©senter un signal dans une base sp√©cifique\n",
    "afin d'effectuer une compression de donn√©es sans trop perdre en qualit√©.\n",
    "Pour un taux de compression √©gal √† 50~\\%, la moiti√© des valeurs de $x$ sont perdues et consid√©r√©es nulles.\n",
    "Bien entendu, il est pr√©f√©rable de supprimer les valeurs les plus faibles pour √©viter de trop modifier le signal.\n",
    "\n",
    "\\begin{questions}\n",

    "x1(idx(1:N/2)) = 0;       % Supprime les N/2 premiers\n",

    "\n",
